# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: magsafe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:magsafe/1-wire] 1-Wire is similar in concept to I2C, but with lower data rates and longer range.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] It is typically used to communicate with small inexpensive devices such as digital thermometers and weather instruments.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] A network of 1-Wire devices with an associated master device is called a **MicroLAN**.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The protocol is also used in small, 16 mm electronic keys known as a **Dallas key** or **iButton**.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] One distinctive feature of the bus is the possibility of using only two conductors — data and ground.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] To accomplish this, 1-Wire devices integrate a small capacitor (~800 pF) to store charge, which powers the device during periods when the data line is active.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] 1-Wire devices are available in different packages: integrated circuits, a TO-92-style package (as typically used for transistors), and a portable form called an iButton or Dallas key which is a small stainless-steel package that resembles a watch battery.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Manufacturers also produce devices more complex than a single component that use the 1-Wire bus to communicate.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] 1-Wire devices can fit in different places in a system.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] It might be one of many components on a circuit board within a product.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] It also might be a single component within a device such as a temperature probe.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] It could be attached to a device being monitored.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Some laboratory systems connect to 1-Wire devices using cables with modular connectors or CAT-5 cable.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] In such systems, RJ11 (6P2C or 6P4C modular plugs, commonly used for telephones) are popular.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Systems of sensors and actuators can be built by wiring together many 1-Wire components.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Each 1-Wire component contains all of the logic needed to operate on the 1-Wire bus.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Examples include temperature loggers, timers, voltage and current sensors, battery monitors, and memory.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] These can be connected to a PC using a bus converter.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] USB, RS-232 serial, and parallel port interfaces are popular solutions for connecting a MicroLan to the host PC.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] 1-Wire devices can also be interfaced directly to microcontrollers from various vendors.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] iButtons are connected to 1-Wire bus systems by means of sockets with contacts that touch the "lid" and "base" of the canister.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Alternatively, the connection can be semi-permanent with a socket into which the iButton clips, but from which it is easily removed.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Each 1-Wire chip has a unique identifier code.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] This feature makes the chips, especially iButtons, suitable electronic keys.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Some uses include locks, burglar alarms, computer systems, manufacturer-approved accessories, time clocks and courier and maintenance keys for smart safes.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] iButtons have been used as Akbil smart tickets for the public transport in Istanbul.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] They can also run smartcard programs such as Java Card 2.0, as exemplified by the "Java Ring" of 1998.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Apple MagSafe- and MagSafe-2-connector–equipped power supplies, displays, and Mac laptops use the 1-Wire protocol to send and receive data to and from the connected Mac laptop, via the middle pin of the connector.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Data include power supply model, wattage, and serial number; and laptop commands to send full power, and illuminate the red or green light-emitting diodes in the connector.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Dell laptop power supplies use the 1-Wire protocol to send data via the third wire to the laptop computer about power, current and voltage ratings.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The laptop will then refuse charging if the adapter does not meet requirements.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] In any MicroLan, there is always one master in overall charge, which may be a personal computer or a microcontroller.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The master initiates activity on the bus, simplifying the avoidance of collisions on the bus.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Protocols are built into the master's software to detect collisions.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] After a collision, the master retries the required communication.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] A 1-Wire network is a single open drain wire with a single pull-up resistor.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The pull-up resistor pulls the wire up to 3 or 5 volts.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The master device and all the slaves each have a single open-drain connection to drive the wire, and a way to sense the state of the wire.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Despite the "1-Wire" name, all devices must also have a second conductor for a ground connection to permit a return current to flow through the data wire.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Communication occurs when a master or slave briefly pulls the bus low, *i.e.*, connects the pull-up resistor to ground through its output MOSFET.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The data wire is high when idle, and so it can also power a limited number of slave devices.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Data rates of 16.3 kbit/s can be achieved.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] There is also an overdrive mode that speeds up the communication by a factor of 10.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] A short 1-Wire bus can be driven from a single digital I/O pin on a microcontroller.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] A universal asynchronous receiver-transmitter (UART) can also be used.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Specific 1-Wire driver and bridge chips are available.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Universal Serial Bus "bridge" chips are also available.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Bridge chips are particularly useful to drive cables longer than 100 m.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Up to 300-meter twisted pairs, *i.e.*, telephone cables, have been tested by the manufacturer.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] These extreme lengths require adjustments to the pull-up resistances from 5 to 1 kΩ.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The master starts a transmission with a *reset* pulse, which pulls the wire to 0 volts for at least 480 μs.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] This resets every slave device on the bus.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] After that, any slave device, if present, shows that it exists with a "presence" pulse: it holds the bus low for at least 60 μs after the master releases the bus.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] To send a binary number "1", the bus master sends a very brief (1–15 μs) low pulse.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] To send a binary number "0", the master sends a 60 μs low pulse.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The falling (negative) edge of the pulse is used to start a monostable multivibrator in the slave device.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The multivibrator in the slave reads the data line about 30 μs after the falling edge.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The slave's internal timer is an inexpensive analog timer.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] It has analog tolerances that affect its timing accuracy.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Therefore, the pulses are calculated to be within margins.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Therefore, the "0" pulses have to be 60 μs long, and the "1" pulses can't be longer than 15 μs.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] When receiving data, the master sends a 1–15 μs 0 volt pulse to start each bit.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] If the transmitting slave unit wants to send a "1", it does nothing, and the bus goes to the pulled-up voltage.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] If the transmitting slave wants to send a "0", it pulls the data line to ground for 60 μs.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The basic sequence is a reset pulse followed by an eight-bit command, and then data are sent or received in groups of eight bits.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] When a sequence of data is being transferred, errors can be detected with an eight-bit CRC (weak data protection)..
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Each device on the bus has a 64-bit serial number, of which eight bits are used as a checksum, thus allowing a "universe" of 256 (over 7.2 × 1016) unique device identities.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The least significant byte of the serial number is an eight-bit number that tells the type of the device.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The most significant byte is a standard (for the 1-Wire bus) eight-bit CRC.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] There are several standard broadcast commands, as well as commands used to address a particular device.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The master can send a selection command, then the address of a particular device.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The next command is executed only by the addressed device.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The 1-Wire bus enumeration protocol, like other singulation protocols, is an algorithm the master uses to read the address of every device on the bus.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Since the address includes the device type and a CRC, recovering the roster of addresses also produces a reliable inventory of the devices on the bus.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] To find the devices, the master broadcasts an enumeration command, and then an address, "listening" after each bit of an address.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] If a slave's address matches all the address bits sent so far, it returns a 0.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The master uses this simple behavior to search systematically for valid sequences of address bits.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The process is much faster than a brute force search of all possible 56-bit numbers, because as soon as an invalid bit is detected, all subsequent address bits are known to be invalid.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The 56-bit address space is searched as a binary tree, allowing up to 75 devices to be found per second.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The order in which device addresses are discovered by this enumeration protocol is deterministic and depends only on the device type and serial number.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Bit-reversing these 56 bits yields the order of discovery for devices using Maxim's published algorithm (algorithm defined in Application Note 187).
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The search algorithm can be implemented in an alternative form, initially searching paths with address bits equal to 1, rather than 0.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] In this case, inverting the 56 address bits and then reversing them yields the order of discovery.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The location of devices on the bus is sometimes significant.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] For these situations, a microcontroller can use several pins, or the manufacturer has a 1-Wire device that can switch the bus off or pass it on.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Software can therefore explore sequential *bus domains*.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Every 1-Wire device's 64-bit ROM ID ends with an 8-bit family code.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] In most cases this byte is assigned to a single part number, so reading it from the bus is usually enough to identify the device—for example, 0x10 (DS18S20 thermometer), 0x01 (DS2401 silicon serial number), or 0x2D (DS2431 1 kbit EEPROM).
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Various people have created online databases of family codes from the broad range of 1-Wire memory, authenticator, ID, and battery-monitor devices.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The following signals were generated by an FPGA, which was the master for the communication with a DS2432 (1 kbit EEPROM with SHA-1 Engine) chip, and measured with a logic analyzer.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] A logic high on the 1-Wire output, means the output of the FPGA is in tri-state mode and the 1-Wire device can pull the bus low.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] A low means the FPGA pulls down the bus.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] The 1-Wire input is the measured bus signal.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] On input sample time high, the FPGA samples the input for detecting the device response and receiving bits.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] When developing and/or troubleshooting the 1-Wire bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:magsafe/1-wire] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools that collect, analyze, decode, and store signals to simplify viewing the high-speed waveforms.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The **Worldwide Developers Conference** (**WWDC**) is an information technology conference held annually by Apple Inc.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The conference is currently held at Apple Park in California.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The event is used to showcase new software and technologies in the macOS, iOS, iPadOS, watchOS, tvOS, and visionOS families as well as other Apple software; new hardware products are sometimes announced as well.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC is also an event hosted for third-party software developers that work on apps for iPhones, iPads, Macs, and other Apple devices.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Attendees can participate in hands-on labs with Apple engineers and attend in-depth sessions covering a wide variety of topics.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The first WWDC was held in 1983, with the introduction of Apple Basic, but it was not until 2002 that Apple started using the conference as a major launchpad for new products.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Beginning in 1987, WWDC was held in Santa Clara.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] After 15 years in nearby San Jose, the conference moved to San Francisco, where it eventually became Apple's primary media event of the year and regularly sold out.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC returned to San Jose 13 years later.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2020 and WWDC 2021 were hosted as online-only conferences due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2022 invited developers and the press back to Apple Park for the first time in about three years despite the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Customers and consumers watched the event via online live streams.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] All of these events were hosted at Apple Park in Cupertino, California.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2023, 2024 and 2025 were held both online and in-person.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The most recent conference, WWDC 2026, was held both online and in-person from June 8 to June 12, 2026.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Until 2020, a $1,599 ticket was required to enter the conference.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Tickets were obtained through an online lottery.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Scholarships are available for students and members of STEM organizations.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Attendees must be 13 years old or older and must be a member of an Apple Developer program.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Until 2007, the number of attendees varied between 2,000 and 4,200; however, during WWDC 2007, Steve Jobs noted that there were more than 5,000 attendees.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The WWDC events held from 2008 to 2015 were capped, and sold out at 5,000 attendees (5,200 including special attendees).
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2018 had 6,000 attendees from 77 countries, including 350 scholarship recipients.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC is held annually from Monday to Friday on one week in June.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The conference consists primarily of a keynote address, presentation sessions, one-on-one "lab" consultations, and special get-togethers and events.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The conference begins with a Monday morning keynote address by Tim Cook and other Apple executives.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] (From 1998 until his resignation and death in 2011, Steve Jobs gave the keynote address, which the media often called the *Stevenote*.) It is attended by both conference attendees and the media, since Apple regularly makes product announcements at the event.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Hardware announced during the address is sometimes exhibited in the conference hall afterwards.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The keynote address is followed in the afternoon by a Platforms State of the Union address, which highlights and demonstrates changes in Apple's software developer platforms that are detailed in sessions later in the week.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The Apple Design Awards are also announced on the first day of the conference.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Several session tracks run simultaneously from Tuesday through Friday.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The presentations cover programming, design, and other topics and range from introductory to advanced.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Almost all regularly scheduled presentations are delivered by Apple employees.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] These presentations are streamed live, and recordings can be viewed on demand on the Apple Developer website in the conference's iOS and tvOS applications.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Lunchtime sessions are given by a variety of guest speakers who are industry experts in technology and science; these sessions are not streamed or recorded.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In the past, some sessions included question-and-answer time, and a popular Stump the Experts session featured interaction between Apple employees and attendees.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] At the labs, which run throughout the week, Apple engineers are available for one-on-one consultations with developers in attendance.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Experts in user interface design and accessibility are also available for consultations by appointment.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple organizes social get-togethers during the conference for various groups, such as women in technology or developers interested in internationalization or machine learning.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The Thursday evening Bash (previously the Beer Bash) at a nearby park features live music, food, and drinks for all attendees 21 years or older.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] During this time, the event was called The Apple Independent Software Developers Conference.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Participants of the event had to sign an NDA, so not much is known about the event, but what is known is that people got a first look at Lisa, the world's first personal computer with a graphical interface.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 1984, Jobs introduced the Macintosh, the second graphical interface personal computer, to developers.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] This was also the first year the conference was open to the media.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The 1986 Apple World Conference was in San Francisco, featuring over 400 exhibitors and 200 companies showcasing Apple II and Macintosh-related products.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Attendees could purchase computer accessories, peripherals, hardware, and software.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple also introduced the monochrome laser printer *LaserWriter Plus* at the conference.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Notable industry experts, such as Stewart Alsop II, David Bunnell, Esther Dyson, Adam Green, and Guy Kawasaki led several conferences.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The AppleWorld Conference 1987 was a two-day event held in Los Angeles on March 2–3, 1987, to celebrate Apple's tenth anniversary and introduce new products.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] At the keynote event, Apple introduced the Macintosh SE and Macintosh II, which was the first Macintosh to support A/UX, Apple's implementation of Unix.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In addition, Apple announced its collaboration with 3Com to develop EtherTalk, an Ethernet-compatible version of the AppleTalk protocol.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] During the opening session, Apple COO Del Yocam, Steve Wozniak, and CEO John Sculley spoke about Apple's history, philosophy, and goals, respectively.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Sculley hinted at Apple's future plans, including a commitment to higher-resolution screens.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The 1987 DevCon was on the first week of April.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In the last week of April, in anticipation of the System 6.0 launch, Apple announced several features that would be included in the release.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] These features included a notification manager that could send data to foreground applications, Macro Maker, a program designed to create keyboard macros, Quickergraf, a performance enhancement to QuickDraw, and enhancements to the system's print monitor.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] For System 7.0, Apple announced additional features, including functions related to interapplication communication, and MultiFinder would become a standard, integrated part of the operating system, replacing Finder.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple also addressed issues related to 32-bit graphics, including Color QuickDraw.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Greater multitasking was also emphasized, in the form of interprocess communications.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In addition to these updates, Bill Atkinson introduced Version 1.2 of HyperCard, which provided support for CD-ROM and other write-protected media.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In the second week of September, Apple announced AppleTalk support for VMS and DECnet.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 1991, WWDC saw the first public demonstration of QuickTime.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 1995, WWDC'95 focused almost fully on the *Copland* project, which by this time was able to be demonstrated to some degree.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Gil Amelio stated that the system was on-schedule to ship in beta form in later summer with an initial commercial release in the very late fall.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] However, very few *live* demos were offered, and no beta of the operating system was offered.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 1996, WWDC'96's primary emphasis was a new software component technology called *OpenDoc*, which allowed end users to compile an application from components offering features they desired most.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The OpenDoc consortium included Adobe, Lotus, others, and Apple.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple touted OpenDoc as the future foundation for application structure under Mac OS.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] As proof of concept, Apple demonstrated a new end-user product called Cyberdog, a comprehensive Internet application component suite offering users an integrated browser, email, FTP, telnet, finger and other services built fully of user-exchangeable OpenDoc components.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] *ClarisWorks* (later renamed *AppleWorks*), a principal product in Apple's wholly owned subsidiary *Claris Corporation*, was demonstrated as an example of a pre-OpenDoc component architecture application modified to be able to contain functional OpenDoc *components*.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 1997, WWDC marked the return of Steve Jobs as a consultant, and his famous reaction to an insult by a developer.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC'97 was the first show after the purchase of NeXT, and focused on the efforts to use OPENSTEP as the foundation of the next Mac OS.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The plan at that time was to introduce a new system then named *Rhapsody*, which would consist of a version of OPENSTEP modified with a more Mac-like look and feel, the *Yellow Box*, along with a *Blue Box* that allowed extant Mac applications to run under OS emulation.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The show focused mainly on the work in progress, including a short history of development efforts since the two development teams had been merged on February 4.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Several new additions to the system were also demonstrated, including tabbed and outline views, and a new object-based graphics layer (NSBezier).
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 1998, in response to developer comments about the new operating system, the *big announcement* at WWDC'98 was the introduction of *Carbon*, effectively a version of the classic Mac OS API implemented on OpenStep.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Under the original Rhapsody plans, classic applications would run in sandboxed installation of the classic Mac OS, (called the Blue Box) and have no access to the new Mac OS X features.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] To receive new features, such as protected memory and preemptive multitasking, developers had to rewrite applications using the Yellow Box API.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Developer complaints about the major porting effort to what was then a shrinking market and warnings that they might simply abandon the platform, led Apple to reconsider the original plan.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Carbon addressed the problem by dramatically reducing the effort needed, while exposing some of the new functions of the underlying OS.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Another major introduction at WWDC'98 was the Quartz imaging model, which replaced Display PostScript with something akin to *display PDF*.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Although the reasons for this switch remain unclear, Quartz also included better support for the extant QuickDraw model from the classic OS, and (as later learned) Java2D.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Supporting QuickDraw directly in the graphics model also led to a related announcement, that the Blue Box would now be *invisible*, integrated into the extant desktop, instead of a separate window.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 1999, WWDC'99 was essentially a *progress report* as the plans outlined in WWDC'98 came to fruition.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Three major announcements were the *opening* of the operating system underlying the new OS as *Darwin*, improvements to the Macintosh Finder, and the replacement of QuickDraw 3D with OpenGL as the primary 3D API.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The system formerly named *OpenStep*, and during development termed *Yellow Box*, was formally renamed *Cocoa*.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2000 was another "progress report" before the upcoming release of Mac OS X.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Recent changes included a modified dock and improved versions of the developer tools.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] *Developer Preview 4* was released at the show, with the commercial release pushed back to January 2001.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Also, WebObjects was dropped in price to a flat fee of US$699.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Approximately 3,600 developers attended and the band The Rippingtons played at the Apple campus.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2001, Mac OS X had only recently been released, but WWDC'01 added the first release of Mac OS X Server and WebObjects 5.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Over 4,000 developers attended, and leather jackets with a large blue "X" embroidered on the back were distributed to attendees.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2002, Mac OS X v.10.2, QuickTime 6 and Rendezvous (now named Bonjour) were presented.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple also said farewell to Mac OS 9 with a mock funeral, and told the developers that no more Mac OS 9 development would occur, reinforcing that the future of the Mac was now entirely on Mac OS X, thus shutting down the Classic Mac OS operating system.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2003, WWDC 2003 demonstrated the Power Mac G5, previewed Mac OS X Panther (10.3), announced the launch of Safari 1.0 (concluding its beta phase), and introduced the *iApps*: iPhoto, iMovie, iDVD, etc.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Attendees received Apple's first model of the iSight web camera (to coincide with the launch of iChat AV), pre-releases of Mac OS X 10.3 and Mac OS X 10.3 Server, the O'Reilly book *Cocoa in a Nutshell*, and a 17-inch notebook carry bag.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple also screened the Pixar film *Finding Nemo* for attendees, ahead of its premiere in cinemas.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Formerly scheduled for May 19 to 23 in San Jose, California, WWDC 2003 was rescheduled for June 23 to 27 at San Francisco's Moscone Center.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Approximately 3,000 developers attended.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2004, WWDC was held from June 28 to July 2.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Jobs noted that 3,500 developers attended, a 17% increase from 2003.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] New displays were introduced in 23- and 30-inch widescreen.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Mac OS X Tiger (10.4) was previewed and iTunes 4.9, the first version with integrated podcast support, was demoed by Jobs.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] All attendees received a developer preview of Tiger, a grey T-shirt with the Apple logo on the front and "WWDC 2004" on the back, a backpack able to hold a 17-inch PowerBook, and a copy of Apple Remote Desktop 2.0.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The band Jimmy Eat World played at the Apple campus after attendees were taken there by bus from Moscone Center West.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] After a basic market update, Jobs announced that Apple would transition the Mac to Intel processors.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The keynote featured developers from Wolfram Research, who discussed their experience porting Mathematica to Mac OS X on the Intel platform.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The conference consisted of 110 lab sessions and 95 presentation sessions, while more than 500 Apple engineers were on site alongside 3,800 attendees from 45 countries.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The band The Wallflowers played at the Apple campus.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2006, Jobs once again delivered the keynote presentation at the WWDC, which was held from August 7 to 11 in Moscone Center West, San Francisco.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The Mac Pro was announced as a replacement to the Power Mac G5, which was Apple's prior *pro* desktop computer and the last remaining PowerPC-based Mac.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The standard Mac Pro featured two 2.66 GHz dual core Xeon (Woodcrest) processors, 1 GB RAM, 250 GB hard drive, and a 256 MB video card.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] An Xserve update, based on the dual core Xeons, was also announced.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Redundant power and Lights Out Management were further product improvements to Apple's server lineup.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Along with the Leopard features that were announced, a major revision to the Mac OS X Server product was announced.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] New features to the Server included: a simplified set-up process, iCal Server (based on the CalDAV standard), Apple Teams (a set of web-based collaborative services), Spotlight Server, and Podcast Producer.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The 2006 WWDC attracted 4,200 developers from 48 countries, while there were 140 sessions and 100 hands-on labs for developers.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] More than 1,000 Apple engineers were present at the event, and the DJ *BT* performed at the Apple Campus in Cupertino.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2007 was held from June 11 to 15 in Moscone Center West, and started with a keynote presentation from Jobs.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple presented a feature-complete beta of Mac OS X Leopard, even though its release date was pushed back to October.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Jobs announced that a version of Safari, Apple's proprietary web browser, had been created for Windows, and that a beta release was being made available online that same day.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple also announced support for third-party development of the then-upcoming iPhone via online web applications running in Safari on the handset.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The announcement implied that Apple, at least for the time being, had no plans to release an iPhone software development kit (SDK), meaning that developers must use *standard web protocols*.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Also, Jobs noted during the keynote that more than 5,000 attendees were present at WWDC 2007, breaking the prior year's record.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The band Ozomatli played at the Yerba Buena Gardens.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2008, WWDC 2008 took place from June 9 to 13 in Moscone Center West.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple reported that, for the first time, the conference had sold out.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] There were three tracks for developers, iPhone, Mac, and IT.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Announcements at the keynote included the App Store for iPhone and iPod Touch, the stable version of the iPhone SDK, a subsidized 3G version of the iPhone for Worldwide markets, version 2.0 of iPhone OS, Mac OS X Snow Leopard (10.6), and the replacement/rebranding of .Mac as MobileMe.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Seven years later, Yahoo News would describe 2008 as "perhaps the peak year for WWDC product intros", which however was marred by problems with MobileMe that caused "one of the biggest PR disasters in Apple history".
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] For the bash held June 12, the band Barenaked Ladies played at the Yerba Buena Gardens.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2009, WWDC 2009 took place from June 8 to 12 in Moscone Center West, and Apple reported that the 2009 conference sold out in late April.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Announcements at the keynote included the release of the iPhone OS 3.0 software announced to developers in March, a demonstration of Mac OS X Snow Leopard (10.6), the new 13" MacBook Pro, updates to the 15" and 17" MacBook Pros, and the new iPhone 3GS.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Phil Schiller, Apple's SVP for Product Marketing, presented the WWDC keynote this year, instead of Jobs, who had taken medical leave of absence since the start of the year.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Attendees received a neoprene messenger bag and the band Cake played at the Yerba Buena Gardens.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] This was the first year plastic badges were used instead of printed paper badges.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2010 was announced on April 28, 2010 and held at Moscone Center West from June 7 to 11.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple reported that the conference was sold out within 8 days of tickets being made available, even though tickets were only available at the full price of US$1599 (2009 and prior, tickets could be bought with an early-bird discount of US$300).
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] On June 7, 2010, Jobs announced the iPhone 4, whose technical problems, combined with Jobs blaming phone owners for them, would dominate the aftermath of the conference ("Antennagate").
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Also at WWDC 2010, the renaming of *iPhone OS* to *iOS* was announced.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The FaceTime and iMovie app for iPhone applications were also announced.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The band OK Go played at the Yerba Buena Gardens.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Attendees received a black track jacket with the letters "WWDC" across the vest and the number "10" stitched on the back.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2011 was held in Moscone Center West from June 6 to 10, 2011.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The event reportedly sold out within just 12 hours of the 5,000 tickets being placed on sale on March 28, 2011.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The ticket price also remained the same from the 2010 WWDC, selling at US$1,599, however, after-market pricing for tickets ranged from US$2,500 to US$3,500.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] At the keynote, Apple unveiled its next generation software: Mac OS X Lion, the eighth major release of Mac OS X; iOS 5, the next version of Apple's advanced mobile operating system which powers the iPad, iPhone and iPod Touch; and iCloud, Apple's upcoming cloud services offering.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Michael Franti and Spearhead played at the Bash in Yerba Buena Gardens on June 9.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Attendees received a black track jacket similar to that of the prior year, but with a smaller "WWDC" across the front and the number "11" stitched on the back.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] This was the final Apple event hosted by Jobs during his lifetime, before his death four months later.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2012 was held in Moscone Center West from June 11 to 15.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The ticket price remained the same as the 2010 WWDC, selling at US$1,599.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple changed the purchasing process by requiring purchases to be made using an Apple ID associated with a paid Apple developer account.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Tickets went on sale shortly after 8:30 am Eastern Time on Wednesday April 25, 2012, and were sold out within 1 hour and 43 minutes.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The keynote highlighted the launch of Apple Maps, and also announced new models of the MacBook Air, and MacBook Pro including one with Retina Display.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple also showcased OS X Mountain Lion and iOS 6.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In prior years, attendees were required to be at least 18 years old.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2012, Apple changed this requirement to at least 13 years after a minor who was "accidentally" awarded a student scholarship in 2011 successfully petitioned Tim Cook to retain the award.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Despite the change, Beer Bash attendees were still required to be 18 years old, and 21 years old to consume alcohol, in accord with local and federal laws.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2013, WWDC 2013 was held from June 10 to 14, 2013 in Moscone Center West.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Tickets went on sale at 10 am PDT on April 25, 2013, selling out within 71 seconds (1 minute and 11 seconds).
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple also announced that it would award 150 free WWDC 2013 Student Scholarship tickets for young attendees to benefit from the conference's many workshops.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In the keynote, Apple unveiled redesigned models of the Mac Pro, AirPort Time Capsule, AirPort Extreme, and MacBook Air, and showcased OS X Mavericks, iOS 7, iWork for iCloud, and a new music streaming service named iTunes Radio.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Vampire Weekend performed at the Bash on June 13 at the Yerba Buena Gardens.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Attendees received a black wind breaker with the letters "WWDC" across the front and the number "13" stitched on the back.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2014 was held from June 2 to 6, 2014 in Moscone Center West.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] For the first time, the opportunity to buy tickets was given at random to developers who were members of an Apple developer program at the time of the conference announcement, and who registered at Apple's developer web site.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple also gave 200 free Student Scholarship tickets.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The keynote began on June 2 and Apple unveiled several new software items, including iOS 8—the largest update to iOS since the release of the App Store—and OS X Yosemite, which features a redesigned interface inspired by iOS.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Announcements included the new programming language Swift, many developer kits and tools for iOS 8, but no new hardware.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Bastille performed at the Yerba Buena Gardens, and attendees received a black windbreaker with the letters "WWDC" across the front and the number "14" stitched on the back, along with a US$25 iTunes gift card to commemorate the 25th anniversary of WWDC.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2015 was held from June 8 to 12, 2015 in Moscone Center West in San Francisco.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The major announcements were the new features of iOS 9, the next version of OS X called OS X El Capitan, the first major software update to the Apple Watch, the June 30 debut of Apple Music, and news that the language Swift was becoming open-source software supporting iOS, OS X, and Linux.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The Beer Bash was held at the Yerba Buena Gardens on June 11.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2016 was held from June 13 to 17, 2016, at the Bill Graham Civic Auditorium and Moscone Center West in San Francisco.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The announcements at the event included renaming OS X to macOS, the new version named macOS Sierra, as well as updates to iOS 10, watchOS 3, and tvOS 10.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple proclaimed that the keynote would be the largest ever for developers; this became the reality when they allowed third-party developers to extend the functionality in Messages, Apple Maps, and Siri.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Cisco Systems and Apple announced a partnership at the 2016 WWDC.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Cisco APIs, accessed through Cisco DevNet, were to have greater interoperability with Apple iOS and APIs.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The keynote was more about software updates and features, as no new hardware was introduced.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple released the Home App that works with HomeKit as a control center for all third-party applications which provide functions for the home.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Also, Swift Playgrounds was announced as an iPad exclusive app that helps younger people learn to code with Apple's programming language Swift.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] APFS, Apple's new file system, was introduced.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The Bash was performed by Good Charlotte at the Bill Graham Civic Auditorium.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2017 (stylized as WWDC17) was held from June 5 to 9, 2017, at the San Jose Convention Center in San Jose, California, which was the first time since 2002 that the conference took place in the city.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Software announcements included iOS 11, watchOS 4, macOS High Sierra, and tvOS 11.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Hardware announcements included updates to iMac, MacBook and MacBook Pro, as well as the new iMac Pro, 10.5-inch iPad Pro and smart speaker HomePod.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Fall Out Boy performed at the Bash held in Discovery Meadow on June 8.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2018 was held from June 4 to 8, 2018, at the San Jose Convention Center in San Jose, California.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The announcements at the event included iOS 12, macOS Mojave, watchOS 5, and tvOS 12.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] As with 2016, there were no new hardware announcements.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Panic! at the Disco performed at the Bash at Discovery Meadow Park.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2019 was held from June 3 to 7, 2019, at the San Jose Convention Center in San Jose, California.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The announcements at the event included iOS 13, macOS Catalina, watchOS 6, tvOS 13, iPadOS 13, the 3rd generation Mac Pro, and the Pro Display XDR.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Weezer performed at the Bash at Discovery Meadow Park.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2020 was held from June 22 to 26, 2020 as an online-only conference for the first time because of the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The announcements at the online Apple Special Event included iOS 14, iPadOS 14, watchOS 7, tvOS 14, macOS Big Sur, and Apple's transition to custom ARM processors for their Macintosh family of personal computers, including a prototype ARM-based Mac for developer use.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The event video footage was recorded at Apple Park in Cupertino, California.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In total, the event got over 22 million views with around 72 hours of content.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2021, with the tag line "Glow and behold.", was held from June 7 to 11, 2021 as another online-only conference also due to the COVID-19 pandemic. iOS 15, iPadOS 15, watchOS 8, tvOS 15, macOS Monterey, and other software updates were announced.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] There were no new hardware announcements at the conference.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] As with 2020, the event video footage was recorded at Apple Park in Cupertino, California.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2022, with the tagline "Call to code.", was held from June 6 to 10, 2022, as an online conference due to the COVID-19 pandemic despite improvements, although there was a special day at Apple Park on June 6, allowing developers and students to watch the online events together.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Despite the COVID-19 pandemic, the event also occurred as an in-person conference for the first time since the previous one held in 2019. iOS 16, iPadOS 16, watchOS 9, tvOS 16 and macOS Ventura were announced at the conference.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Stage Manager for Macs was also introduced during the initial presentation.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Hardware announcements included the M2 chip and updated MacBook Air and 13-inch MacBook Pro models based on it.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2023, with the tagline "Code new worlds" was held from June 5 to 9 in an online format with an in-person experience at Apple Park on the first day of the show.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Similarly to the previous years, Apple held the Swift Student Challenge, launched in 2020 for the first time, with applications through April 19 and results on May 9.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Prizes included WWDC outerwear, AirPods Pro, a customized pin set, and a one-year membership in the Apple Developer Program.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Among the winners, some were randomly chosen to attend the Apple Park special event.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] For software, Apple introduced macOS 14 Sonoma, the 20th major release of macOS, as well as iOS 17, iPadOS 17, watchOS 10, tvOS 17 and firmware updates to AirPods.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] For hardware, they announced the Apple M2 Ultra SoC for Macs, 15-inch MacBook Air with M2, Mac Studio with M2 Max and Ultra and the Mac Pro with M2 Ultra.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] They also unveiled an AR/VR headset under the name of "Apple Vision Pro", which would have games and experiences developed with Unity.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] As with 2021, no new hardware was announced at the conference.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] No new hardware was announced at the conference.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] WWDC 2026, with the tagline "All systems glow", took place from June 8 to 12, 2026, in an online format with an in-person event at Apple Park on June 8. iOS 27, iPadOS 27, watchOS 27, macOS Golden Gate, tvOS 27, and visionOS 27 were announced at that event.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2020, due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Apple replaced the annual WWDC Scholarships with the Swift Student Challenge, a programming contest held before WWDC which centers on the Swift programming language.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] As of 2020, the program was managed by Apple head of developer marketing Esther Hare.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] 350 winners are selected, who receive WWDC-themed clothing, a metal pin set, the ability to meet Apple engineers, a one-year membership of the Apple Developer Program, and since 2022, a pair of AirPods Pro.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2022, Tim Cook met with 12 of the winners.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] In 2023, students could also enter a lottery for in-person attendance of WWDC at Apple Park.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The task is to create an interactive scene, shorter than 3 minutes, inside Swift Playgrounds*,* an Apple app that teaches introductory programming.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The projects are judged based on technical accomplishment, creativity, and the text accompanying the submission.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] The challenge is only open to students 13 or older in the United States, or the minimum age in their jurisdiction (for example, 16 in the European Union) who are currently enrolled in an accredited school or have recently graduated, and who are not working full-time as developers.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Students can win the award up to four times.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Students may win the Distinguished Winner award up to one time.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Several third-party conferences are held in conjunction with WWDC each year, including AltConf, Layers, and NextDoor.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Prominent podcasters Jim Dalrymple and John Gruber hold events nearby, and former Apple evangelist James Dempsey performs a benefit concert.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Previously, Apple also announced new products at Macworld Expo and Apple Expo.
[src:magsafe/2012-worldwide-developers-conference] Apple continues to hold "special events" throughout the year for product introductions, and on rare occasions releases products without holding an event.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:magsafe/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] It is best known as the world's biggest online shopping retailer and marketplace, offering a wide range of products and services.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon sells books, electronics, pharmaceuticals, car parts, video games, dining products, jewelry, food, music, and sports equipment.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The company has multiple subsidiaries, including Amazon Web Services (AWS), which provides cloud computing; Zoox, a self-driving car division; Kuiper Systems, a satellite Internet provider; and Amazon Lab126, a computer hardware R&D provider.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Other subsidiaries include Ring, Twitch, IMDb, and Whole Foods Market.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Its acquisition of Whole Foods in August 2017 for US$13.4 billion substantially increased its market share and its presence as a physical retailer.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also distributes a variety of downloadable and streaming content through its Amazon Prime Video, MGM+, Amazon Music, Twitch, Audible, and Wondery units.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also produces consumer electronics, most notably Kindle e-readers, Echo devices, Fire tablets, and Fire TVs.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has a reputation as a disruptor of industries through technological innovation and aggressive reinvestment of profits into capital expenditures.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As of 2023, it is the world's largest online retailer and marketplace, smart speaker provider, cloud computing service provider through AWS, live-streaming service provider through Twitch, and Internet company as measured by revenue and market share.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2021, it surpassed Walmart as the world's largest retailer outside of China, driven in large part by its paid subscription plan, Amazon Prime, which has 200 million subscribers worldwide.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] It is the second-largest private employer in the United States and the second-largest company in the world and the United States by revenue as of 2024 (after Walmart).
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As of October 2024, Amazon is the 12th-most visited website in the world, and 84% of its traffic comes from the United States.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has been criticized for its business practices, including surveillance partnerships, poor working conditions, anti-union efforts, environmental harm, anticompetitive behavior, censorship controversies, and exploitative treatment of small businesses and suppliers.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On July 5, 1994, Amazon was founded as "Cadabra" by Jeff Bezos, after he relocated from New York City to Bellevue, Washington, near Seattle, to operate an online bookstore.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Bezos chose the Seattle area for its abundance of technical talent from Microsoft and the University of Washington, as well as its smaller population for sales tax purposes and the proximity to a major book distribution warehouse in Roseburg, Oregon.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Other options Bezos considered included Portland, Oregon, and Boulder, Colorado.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] A few months later, in November 1994, Cadabra, which had been founded in the converted garage of Bezos's house for symbolic reasons, was renamed to Amazon.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On July 16, 1995, the Amazon website launched for public sales, initially sourcing its books directly from wholesalers and publishers.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Bezos retained the URL www.relentless.com, which he purchased when considering a name for the company; it redirects to the Amazon homepage.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 1998, Amazon began selling music and videos, and began international operations by acquiring online sellers of books in the United Kingdom and Germany.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In the subsequent year, it initiated the sale of a diverse range of products, including music, video games, consumer electronics, home improvement items, software, games, and toys.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2002, the company launched Amazon Web Services (AWS), which initially focused on providing APIs for web developers to build web applications on top of Amazon's e-commerce platform.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2004, AWS was expanded to provide website popularity statistics and web crawler data from the Alexa Web Information Service.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] AWS later shifted toward providing enterprise services with Simple Storage Service (S3) in 2006, and Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) in 2008, allowing companies to rent data storage and computing power from Amazon.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2006, Amazon launched the*Fulfillment by Amazon*program, which allowed individuals and small companies (called "third-party sellers") to sell products through Amazon's warehouses and fulfillment infrastructure.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon purchased the Whole Foods Market supermarket chain in 2017.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] It is the leading e-retailer in the United States with approximately US$178 billion net sales in 2017.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] It has over 300 million active customer accounts globally.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon saw large growth during the COVID-19 pandemic, hiring more than 100,000 staff in the United States and Canada.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Some Amazon workers in the US, France, and Italy protested the company's decision to "run normal shifts" due to COVID-19's ease of spread in warehouses.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In Spain, the company faced legal complaints over its policies, while a group of US Senators wrote an open letter to Bezos expressing concerns about workplace safety.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On February 2, 2021, Bezos announced that he would step down as CEO to become executive chair of Amazon's board.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The transition officially took place on July 5, 2021, with former CEO of AWS Andy Jassy replacing him as CEO.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In January 2023, Amazon cut over 18,000 jobs, primarily in consumer retail and its human resources division in an attempt to cut costs.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On November 8, 2023, a plan was adopted for Jeff Bezos to sell approximately 50 million shares of the company over the next year with a deadline of January 31, 2025.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The first step was the sale of 12 million shares for about $2 billion.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On February 26, 2024, Amazon became a component of the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On December 19, 2024, Amazon workers, led by the International Brotherhood of Teamsters labor union, went on strike against Amazon in at least four US states, with workers in other facilities in the United States being welcomed to join the strike as well.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On October 28, 2025, the company announced plans to reduce its corporate workforce by 14,000 positions, which has been reported as the largest round of job cuts by Amazon since 2022.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As part of this plan, Amazon is expected to fire about 370 people from its European headquarters in Luxembourg in December 2025 to early 2026.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon announced a second round of large-scale layoffs, affecting approximately 16,000 corporate employees.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] This followed the earlier reduction of 14,000 positions in October 2025.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] According to company statements and news reports, the layoffs were part of a broader effort to streamline operations, reduce bureaucracy, and adapt to changing business conditions, including the adoption of artificial intelligence technologies.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Affected employees were offered severance packages and support for internal job placement.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In January 2025, Amazon filed an objection to Saks Global’s bankruptcy financing plan.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon invested $475 million into Saks’ acquisition of Neiman Marcus, and is now worried that Saks declaring bankruptcy would harm creditors and push the tech company further down the repayment pecking order.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon entered talks with OpenAI to invest up to $50 billion.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon historically has a deep strategic partnership with Anthropic, OpenAI's competitor.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon also laid off 16,000 employees in what is Amazon's second round of large-scale job reductions in three months due to AI.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In February 2026, Amazon said it expected to invest $12 billion in Louisiana as part of a plan to build data centers there.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] This plan will create 540 full-time jobs.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In March 2026, Amazon signed an energy pledge at the White House which required it to bear the cost of new electricity generation to power its data centers.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon launched Amazon Supply Chain Services in May 2026.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon websites are country-specific (for example, amazon.com for the US and amazon.co.uk for UK) though some offer international shipping.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Visits to *amazon.com* grew from 615 million annual visitors in 2008, to more than 2 billion per month in 2022.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The e-commerce platform is the 12th most visited website in the world.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In February 2024, Amazon announced its first chatbot, "Rufus", for use in the US; in July it was widely available to all customers in the US.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] "Rufus" is now available in the US, India and the UK which helps the shoppers get product recommendations, get shopping list advice, compare products and see what other customers have responded to regarding their specific questions.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Results generated by Amazon's search engine are partly determined by promotional fees.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2004, Toys "R" Us sued Amazon, claiming that because of a perceived lack of variety in Toys "R" Us stock, Amazon had knowingly allowed third-party sellers to offer items on the service in categories that Toys "R" Us had been granted exclusivity.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2006, a court ruled in favor of Toys "R" Us, giving it the right to unwind its agreement with Amazon and establish its independent e-commerce website.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The company was later awarded $51 million in damages.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2001, Amazon entered into a similar agreement with Borders, under which Amazon would comanage Borders.com as a co-branded service.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Borders pulled out of the arrangement in 2007, with plans to also launch its own online store.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On October 18, 2011, Amazon.com announced a partnership with DC Comics for the exclusive digital rights to many popular comics, including *Superman*, *Batman*, *Green Lantern*, *Sandman*, and *Watchmen*.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The partnership has caused well-known bookstores like Barnes & Noble to remove these titles from its shelves.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In November 2013, Amazon announced a partnership with the United States Postal Service to begin delivering orders on Sundays.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The service, included in Amazon's standard shipping rates, initiated in metropolitan areas of Greater Los Angeles and New York because of the high-volume and inability to deliver in a timely way, with plans to expand into Dallas, Houston, New Orleans and Phoenix by 2014.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In June 2017, Nike agreed to sell products through Amazon in exchange for better policing of counterfeit goods.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] This proved unsuccessful and Nike withdrew from the partnership in November 2019.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Companies including IKEA and Birkenstock also stopped selling through Amazon around the same time, citing similar frustrations over business practices and counterfeit goods.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In September 2017, Amazon ventured with one of its sellers JV Appario Retail owned by Patni Group which has recorded a total income of US$104.44 million (₹759 crore) in financial year 2017–2018.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As of October 11, 2017, Amazon Fresh sold a range of Booths branded products for home delivery in selected areas.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In November 2018, Amazon reached an agreement with Apple Inc. to sell selected products through the service, via the company and selected Apple Authorized Resellers.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As a result of this partnership, only Apple Authorized Resellers may sell Apple products on Amazon effective January 4, 2019.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On November 7, 2024, Amazon is reportedly discussing a second multi-billion dollar investment in AI startup Anthropic, following its initial $4 billion investment.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On 8 October 2025, Amazon launched prescription vending machines at One Medical clinics in Los Angeles.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The machines are operated by Amazon Pharmacy and are able to prescribe a range of common medications, such as antibiotics, inhalers and blood pressure treatments.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon sells many products under its own brand names, including phone chargers, batteries, and diaper wipes.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The AmazonBasics brand was introduced in 2009, and now features hundreds of product lines, including smartphone cases, computer mice, batteries, dumbbells, and dog crates.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon owned 34 private-label brands as of 2019.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] These brands account for 0.15% of Amazon's global sales, whereas the average for other large retailers is 18%.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Other Amazon retail brands include Presto!, Mama Bear, and Amazon Essentials.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon derives many of its sales (around 40% in 2008) from third-party sellers who sell products on Amazon.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Some other large e-commerce sellers use Amazon to sell their products in addition to selling them through their websites.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The sales are processed through Amazon.com and end up at individual sellers for processing and order fulfillment and Amazon leases space for these retailers.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Small sellers of used and new goods go to Amazon Marketplace to offer goods at a fixed price.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Publishers can sign up as affiliates and receive a commission for referring customers to Amazon by placing links to Amazon on their websites if the referral results in a sale.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Worldwide, Amazon has "over 900,000 members" in its affiliate programs.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As of mid-2014, the Amazon Affiliate Program was used by 1.2% of all websites and was the second most popular advertising network after Google Ads.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] It is frequently used by websites and non-profits to provide a way for supporters to earn them a commission.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Associates can access the Amazon catalog directly on their websites by using the Amazon Web Services (AWS) XML service.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] A new affiliate product, aStore, allows Associates to embed a subset of Amazon products within another website, or linked to another website.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In June 2010, Amazon Seller Product Suggestions was launched to provide more transparency to sellers by recommending specific products to third-party sellers to sell on Amazon.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Products suggested are based on customers' browsing history.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] A link -- embedded in a book name in an online article in *The New Yorker* and prefixed *cna.st/affiliate-link/* (the magazine is owned by Condé Nast) -- automatically redirected when accessed to the appropriate *amazon.com* page for the book.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon allows users to submit reviews to the web page of each product.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Reviewers must rate the product on a rating scale from one to five stars.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon provides a badging option for reviewers that indicates the real name of the reviewer (based on confirmation of a credit card account) or that indicates that the reviewer is one of the top reviewers by popularity.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As of 16 December 2020, Amazon removed the ability of sellers and customers to comment on product reviews and purged their websites of all posted product review comments.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In an email to sellers, Amazon gave its rationale for removing this feature: "...the comments feature on customer reviews was rarely used." The remaining review response options are to indicate whether the reader finds the review helpful or to report that it violates Amazon policies (abuse).
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] If a review is given enough "helpful" hits, it appears on the front page of the product.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2010, Amazon was reported as being the largest single source of Internet consumer reviews.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] When publishers asked Bezos why Amazon would publish negative reviews, he defended the practice by claiming that Amazon.com was "taking a different approach...we want to make every book available—the good, the bad and the ugly...to let truth loose".
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] There have been cases of positive reviews being written and posted by public relations companies on behalf of their clients and instances of writers using pseudonyms to leave negative reviews of their rivals' works.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The Amazon sales rank (ASR) indicates the popularity of a product sold on any Amazon locale.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] It is a relative indicator of popularity that is updated hourly.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Effectively, it is a "best sellers list" for the millions of products stocked by Amazon.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] While the ASR has no direct effect on the sales of a product, it is used by Amazon to determine which products to include in its bestsellers lists.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Products that appear in these lists enjoy additional exposure on the Amazon website and this may lead to an increase in sales.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In particular, products that experience large jumps (up or down) in their sales ranks may be included within Amazon's lists of "movers and shakers"; such a listing provides additional exposure that might lead to an increase in sales.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] For competitive reasons, Amazon does not release actual sales figures to the public.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] However, Amazon has now begun to release point of sale data via the BookScan service to verified authors.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] While the ASR has been the source of much speculation by publishers, manufacturers, and marketers, Amazon itself does not release the details of its sales rank calculation algorithm.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In November 2015, Amazon opened a physical Amazon Books store in University Village in Seattle.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The store was 5,500 square feet and prices for all products matched those on its website.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon opened its tenth physical bookstore in 2017; media speculation at the time suggested that Amazon planned to eventually roll out 300 to 400 bookstores around the country.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] All of its locations were closed in 2022 along with other retail locations under the "Amazon 4-Star" brand.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In July 2016, the company announced that it was opening a 1,100,000 ft (335,280.0 m) square foot facility in Palmer Township in the Lehigh Valley region of eastern Pennsylvania.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As of 2024, Amazon is the Lehigh Valley region's third-largest employer.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In August 2019, Amazon applied to have a liquor store in San Francisco, as a means to ship beer and alcohol within the city.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2020, Amazon Fresh opened several physical stores in the US and the United Kingdom.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon announced it would close all of its Amazon Go and Amazon Fresh stores to shift focus to its online same-day delivery service and expand its Whole Foods Market business.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The closure affects 57 Fresh stores and 15 Amazon Go locations, some of which will be converted into Whole Foods stores.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has a number of products and services available, including its digital assistant Alexa, Amazon Music, and Prime Video for music and videos respectively, the Amazon Appstore for Android apps, the Kindle line of electronic paper e-readers, Fire and Fire HD color LCD tablets.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Audible provides audiobooks for purchase and listening.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In September 2021, Amazon announced the launch of Astro, its first household robot, powered by its Alexa smart home technology.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] This can be remote-controlled when not at home, to check on pets, people, or home security.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] It will send owners a notification if it detects something unusual.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In January 2023, Amazon announced the launch of RXPass, a prescription drug delivery service.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Prime members to pay a $5 monthly fee for access to 60 medications.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The service was launched immediately after the announcement except in states with specific prescription delivery requirements.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Beneficiaries of government healthcare programs such as Medicare and Medicaid will not be able to sign up for RXPass.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon owns over 100 subsidiaries, including Amazon Web Services, Audible, Diapers.com, Goodreads, IMDb, Kiva Systems (now Amazon Robotics), One Medical, Shopbop, Teachstreet, Twitch, Zappos, and Zoox.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Bezos separately owns *The Washington Post* (through Nash Holdings, LLC), Blue Origin, Bezos Expeditions, Altos Labs, and other companies.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Live is a video e-commerce live-streaming service created to compete with live-streaming services.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The service allows users to stream live videos promoting or sponsoring products.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Users (mainly celebrities or Internet influencers) have the option to livestream on Amazon and add tags to additionally add context to the products they're selling or promoting.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Other users can join in and type in messages to send to a global chat on the livestream.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2019 Amazon launched an integrated platform into the Amazon website and application.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In 2023 roughly a billion total viewers watch Amazon Live across the United States and India.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The platform has also been integrated into Amazon Freevee and Amazon Prime Video.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Web Services (AWS) is a subsidiary of Amazon that provides on-demand cloud computing platforms and APIs to individuals, companies, and governments, on a metered pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] These cloud computing web services provide distributed computing processing capacity and software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As of 2021 Q4, AWS has 33% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 21%, and 10% respectively, according to Synergy Group.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Audible is a seller and producer of spoken audio entertainment, information, and educational programming on the Internet.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Audible sells digital audiobooks, radio and television programs, and audio versions of magazines and newspapers.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Through its production arm, Audible Studios, Audible has also become the world's largest producer of downloadable audiobooks.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On January 31, 2008, Amazon announced it would buy Audible for about $300 million.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The deal closed in March 2008 and Audible became a subsidiary of Amazon.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Goodreads is a "social cataloging" website founded in December 2006 and launched in January 2007 by Otis Chandler, a software engineer, and entrepreneur, and Elizabeth Khuri.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The website allows individuals to freely search Goodreads' extensive user-populated database of books, annotations, and reviews.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Users can sign up and register books to generate library catalogs and reading lists.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] They can also create their groups of book suggestions and discussions.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In December 2007, the site had over 650,000 members, and over a million books had been added.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon bought the company in March 2013.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Ring is a home automation company founded by Jamie Siminoff in 2013.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] It is primarily known for its Wi-Fi powered smart doorbells, but manufactures other devices such as security cameras.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon bought Ring for US$1 billion in 2018.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Twitch is a live streaming platform for video, primarily oriented towards video gaming content.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Twitch was acquired by Amazon in August 2014 for $970 million.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The site's rapid growth had been boosted primarily by the prominence of major esports competitions on the service, leading *GameSpot* senior esports editor Rod Breslau to have described the service as "the ESPN of esports".
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As of 2015, the service had over 1.5 million broadcasters and 100 million monthly viewers.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Whole Foods Market is an American supermarket chain exclusively featuring foods without artificial preservatives, colors, flavors, sweeteners, and hydrogenated fats.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon acquired Whole Foods for $13.7 billion in August 2017.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Since acquiring Whole Foods, the company has launched its own chain of Fresh supermarkets and taken steps to integrate its online and physical grocery operations.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also has investments in renewable energy, including plans to fund four small nuclear reactors at the Xe-100 reactor site in Eastern Washington, and plans to expand its position into the Canadian market through an investment in a new plant in Alberta.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's global headquarters are in more than 40 owned and leased buildings spread across Seattle's adjacent South Lake Union, Denny Triangle, and Downtown neighborhoods.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The first 14 buildings Amazon occupied in South Lake Union were developed primarily by Vulcan, Inc. from 2008 onward, the first 11 of which were acquired from Vulcan in 2012 at a cost of $1.16 billion.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The company was previously headquartered in rented space within the Pacific Medical Center, located in the city's Beacon Hill neighborhood, from 1998 to 2011.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon is currently building a new four tower, four low-rise, complex in Seattle's Denny Triangle neighborhood to serve as the primary headquarters, though it will retain many of the earlier purchased buildings to house its more than 45,000 corporate employees in the Seattle area.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The plan for the new campus, designed by NBBJ and named "Rufus 2.0" after a dog who was a fixture of the company in its early days, was approved by the city of Seattle in 2012 and construction began the year after.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The first of the towers, nicknamed Doppler, opened on December 14, 2015.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's European headquarters are in Luxembourg's capital, Luxembourg.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Its UK headquarters are at Principal Place, Shoreditch, London.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On November 13, 2018, Amazon announced that it would divide the planned HQ2 between New York City and Northern Virginia.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On February 14, 2019, Amazon canceled its plan for the HQ2 location in New York City.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon is also in the process of building a retail hub of operations center in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On August 21, 2019, Amazon opened its largest campus in the world at Nanakramguda in Hyderabad, India.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] It is the first Amazon-owned campus located outside the United States and features the single largest Amazon-owned building in the world.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The 9.5-acre campus houses over 15,000 employees.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon plans to build a major campus in Bellevue, Washington, a suburb of Seattle, that will host 15,000 employees by 2025.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The company opened its first Bellevue office in 2017, marking a return to the city since the company was founded there in 1995.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's largest building in the city is Sonic, a 42-story building developed by Vulcan Real Estate with 1 million square feet (93,000 m2) of office space.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The Bellevue campus will include the 43-story Bellevue 600 tower, which is planned to be the tallest building in the city and the tallest to be developed by Amazon.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] While much of Amazon's software development occurs in Seattle, the company employs software developers in centers across the globe.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Some of these sites are run by an Amazon subsidiary called A2Z Development.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has operated various retail store brands.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Most of the stores are located inside of the United States, but Whole Foods also operates stores in Canada and the United Kingdom, while Amazon Go has six locations in London under the Amazon Fresh name.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon uses many different transportation services to deliver packages.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon directly employs people to work at its warehouses, bulk distribution centers, staffed "Amazon Hub Locker+" locations, and delivery stations where drivers pick up packages.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] As of December 2020, it is not hiring delivery drivers as employees.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Rakuten Intelligence estimated that in 2020 in the United States, the proportion of last-mile deliveries was 56% by Amazon's directly contracted services (mostly in urban areas), 30% by the United States Postal Service (mostly in rural areas), and 14% by UPS.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In April 2021, Amazon reported to investors it had increased its in-house delivery capacity by 50% in the last 12 months (which included the first year of the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States).
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In addition to Amazon Lockers, Amazon has around 30 staffed pickup points in the United States and over 800 independent ones in India.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The US locations have large sets of Amazon Lockers and an area for customers to make returns.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The India locations are in existing retailers and have customers wait for a store employee to retrieve their package.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon first launched its distribution network in 1997 with two fulfillment centers in Seattle and New Castle, Delaware.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has several types of distribution facilities consisting of cross-dock centers, fulfillment centers, sortation centers, delivery stations, Prime now hubs, and Prime air hubs.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] There are 75 fulfillment centers and 25 sortation centers with over 125,000 employees.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Employees are responsible for five basic tasks: unpacking and inspecting incoming goods; placing goods in storage and recording their location; picking goods from their computer recorded locations to make up an individual shipment; sorting and packing orders; and shipping.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] A computer that records the location of goods and maps out routes for pickers plays a key role: employees carry hand-held computers which communicate with the central computer and monitor their rate of progress.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Some warehouses are partially automated with systems built by Amazon Robotics.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In September 2006, Amazon launched a program called FBA (Fulfillment By Amazon) whereby it could handle storage, packing and distribution of products and services for small sellers.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon fulfillment centers are large facilities with hundreds of employees, sometimes thousands.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] A picker may walk 10 or more miles a day.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In newer fulfillment centers, items are stored on pods and brought to pickers by robots (Amazon Robotics).
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In the United Kingdom, initial staffing was provided by Randstad NV and other temporary employment agencies.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In the United States, many workers are hired as Amazon employees and granted shares of stock or sign-on bonuses, while others are offered temporary seasonal positions.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] "When we have permanent positions available, we look to the top-performing temporary associates to fill them," said an Amazon spokesperson.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon acquired Kiva Systems, a warehouse automation company, in 2012.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Amazon fulfillment centers can also provide warehousing and order-fulfillment for third-party sellers, for an extra fee.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] Third-party sellers can use Fulfillment by Amazon (FBA) to ship for other platforms as well, such as eBay or their own websites.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] On March 20, 2020, Amazon agreed to remove metal detectors from its warehouses after a warehouse worker tested positive for COVID-19.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] In addition to removing metal detectors, Amazon enacted a "6 feet rule", which enforced a six-feet distance between warehouse employees.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p01] The Federal Public Health Emergency (PHE) for COVID-19 (which included social distancing) declared under Section 319 of the Public Health Service (PHS) Act, expired at the end of the day on May 11, 2023.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com is primarily a retail site with a sales revenue model; Amazon takes a small percentage of the sale price of each item that is sold through its website while also allowing companies to advertise their products by paying to be listed as featured products.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] As of 2018, Amazon.com is ranked eighth on the Fortune 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In Forbes Global 2000 2023 Amazon ranked 36th.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] For the fiscal year 2021, Amazon reported earnings of US$33.36 billion, with an annual revenue of US$469.82 billion, an increase of 21.7% over the previous fiscal cycle.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Since 2007 sales increased from 14.835 billion to 469.822 billion, due to continued business expansion.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Amazon's market capitalization went over US$1 trillion again in early February 2020 after the announcement of the fourth quarter 2019 results.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] During his tenure, Jeff Bezos had become renowned for his annual shareholder letters, which have gained similar notability to those of Warren Buffett.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] These annual letters gave an "invaluable window" into the famously "secretive" company, and revealed Bezos's perspectives and strategic focus.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] A common theme of these letters is Bezos's desire to instill customer-centricity (in his words, "customer obsession") at all levels of Amazon, notably by making all senior executives field customer support queries for a short time at Amazon call centers.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] He also read many emails addressed by customers to his public email address.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] One of Bezos's most well-known internal memos was his mandate for "all teams" to "expose their data and functionality" through service interfaces "designed from the ground up to be externalizable".
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] This process, commonly known as a service-oriented architecture (SOA), resulted in mandatory dogfooding of services that would later be commercialized as part of AWS.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Amazon has used internal recognition programs such as the Just Do It Award to encourage employee initiative and experimentation.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Amazon lobbies the United States federal government and state governments on multiple issues such as the enforcement of sales taxes on online sales, transportation safety, privacy and data protection and intellectual property.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] According to regulatory filings, Amazon.com focuses its lobbying on the United States Congress, the Federal Communications Commission and the Federal Reserve.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com spent roughly $3.5 million, $5 million and $9.5 million on lobbying, in 2013, 2014 and 2015, respectively.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In 2019, it spent $16.8 million and had a team of 104 lobbyists.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com was a corporate member of the American Legislative Exchange Council (ALEC) until it dropped membership following protests at its shareholders' meeting on May 24, 2012.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In 2014, Amazon expanded its lobbying practices as it prepared to lobby the Federal Aviation Administration to approve its drone delivery program, hiring the Akin Gump Strauss Hauer & Feld lobbying firm in June.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Amazon and its lobbyists have visited with Federal Aviation Administration officials and aviation committees in Washington, D.C. to explain its plans to deliver packages.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In September 2020 this moved one step closer with the granting of a critical certificate by the FAA.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] During the second Trump Administration, Amazon donated several times to various events and aspects of his presidency.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Along with several other major companies, Amazon donated $1 million to Trump's inaugural fund.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In April 2025, Amazon was a corporate sponsor of the White House Easter Egg Roll, after Donald Trump solicited corporate sponsors for the event for the first time.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In October 2025, Amazon was listed among the donors funding the construction of the White House State Ballroom.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Amazon lobbies on climate policy internationally.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In the US, following Trump’s 2025 inauguration, Amazon began frequent engagements with the executive branch to advocate for permitting reform and energy development to support data center growth.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In July 2025, Amazon joined policymakers at the Pennsylvania Energy and Innovation Summit, where it supported the development of nuclear energy to meet growing electricity demand, and lobbied for permitting reform to support grid development nationwide.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] A December 2025 DeSmog article reported that the company’s sponsorship came alongside several organizations that had supported climate change denial, and a continued role for fossil fuels to meet growing energy demand.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Criticism has also concerned various decisions over whether to censor or publish content such as the WikiLeaks website, works containing libel, anti-LGBT merchandise, and material facilitating dog fighting, cockfighting, or pedophile activities.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] An article published by *Time* in the wake of social media website Parler's termination of service by Amazon Web Service highlights the power companies like Amazon now have over the internet.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In December 2011, Amazon faced a backlash from small businesses for running a one-day deal to promote its new Price Check app.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Shoppers who used the app to check prices in a brick-and-mortar store were offered a 5% discount to purchase the same item from Amazon.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Companies like Groupon, eBay and Taap have countered Amazon's promotion by offering $10 off from its products.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] The company has also faced accusations of putting undue pressure on suppliers to maintain and extend its profitability.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In 2019, Amazon banned selling skin-lightening products after pushback from Minnesota health and environmental activists.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In 2022, a lawsuit filed by state attorney-general Letitia James was dismissed by the New York state court of appeals.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] After the COVID-19 pandemic, Amazon faced criticism for complying, under pressure from the Biden Administration, to "reduce the visibility" of books critical of the COVID-19 vaccine, which was revealed after Rep.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Jim Jordan (acting on behalf of the House Judiciary Committee) subpoenaed emails between the company and the Biden Administration.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Amazon Prime has been criticized for its vehicles systemically double parking, blocking bike lanes, and otherwise violating traffic laws while dropping off packages, contributing to traffic congestion and endangering other road users.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Jane Friedman discovered six listings of books fraudulently using her name, on Amazon and Goodreads.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In 2024, following years of criticism for providing law enforcement footage in the custody of Ring (a home security company owned by Amazon) without a warrant, Ring has halted this practice.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] It received cautious praise from privacy-focused organizations such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation for this change.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In February 2025, Sky accused Amazon of not doing enough to prevent the piracy of its sports rights via "jailbroken" Fire Sticks.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Project Nimbus is a contract by which Amazon and Google provide Israel and its military with artificial intelligence, machine learning, and other cloud-computing services.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] The contract has been criticized by shareholders and employees concerned that the project may lead to abuses of Palestinian human rights in the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In October 2025, Amazon suspended an employee who posted messages to the company's Slack and wrote a letter to Andy Jassy criticizing Nimbus.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] On July 22, 2025, Amazon announced its plan to acquire San Francisco-based startup Bee AI.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] Bee produces a wristband, similar to most modern smartwatches, equipped with AI and microphones.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] The wristband is capable of providing summaries of conversations and reminders of tasks, effectively serving as a 24/7 note taker.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] News outlets criticize the fact that the devices saves transcripts, potentially utilizing it to train generative AI models which require vast quantities of data.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] In January 2026, Amazon sent a notice out to cloud staffers in an apparent error acknowledging “organizational changes” at the company.
[src:magsafe/amazon-company-p02] The note also mentioned a "Project Dawn" which was cancelled, although it is unclear what the project is about.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] The color **amber** is a pure chroma color, located on the color wheel midway between the colors of yellow and orange.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] The color name is derived from the material also known as amber, which is commonly found in a range of yellow-orange-brown-red colors; likewise, as a color, *amber* can refer to a range of yellow-orange colors.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] In English, the first recorded use of the term as a color name, rather than a reference to the specific substance, was in 1500.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] Amber is one of several technically defined colors used in automotive signal lamps.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] In North America, SAE standard J578 governs the colorimetry of vehicle lights, while outside North America the internationalized European ECE regulations hold force.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] Both standards designate a range of orange-yellow hues in the CIE color space as "amber".
[src:magsafe/amber-color] In the past, the ECE amber definition was more restrictive than the SAE definition, but the current ECE definition is identical to the more permissive SAE standard.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] The SAE formally uses the term "yellow amber", though the color is most often referred to as "yellow".
[src:magsafe/amber-color] This is not the same as selective yellow, a color used in some fog lamps and headlamps.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] The entirety of these definitions lie outside the gamut of the sRGB color space — such a pure color cannot be represented using RGB primaries.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] The color box shown above is a desaturated approximation, produced by taking the centroid of the standard definition and moving it towards the D65 white point, until it meets the sRGB gamut triangle.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] The color temperature of LED lamps is called amber when their wavelengths are about 590 nm.
[src:magsafe/amber-color] Chronomatic low-pressure sodium-vapor lamps emit light ranging from 580 to 590 nm.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The company was founded to market Wozniak's Apple I personal computer.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Its successor, the Apple II, became one of the first successful mass-produced microcomputers.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple introduced the Lisa in 1983 and the Macintosh in 1984 as some of the first computers to use a graphical user interface and a mouse.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] By 1985, internal conflicts led to Jobs leaving the company to form NeXT and Wozniak withdrawing to other ventures; John Sculley was CEO for over a decade.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In the 1990s, Apple lost considerable market share in the PC industry to the lower-priced Wintel duopoly of Intel-powered PC clones running Windows, and was reporting major losses by 1997.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] To overhaul its market strategy, Apple acquired NeXT, bringing Jobs back to the company.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Under his leadership, Apple returned to profitability by introducing the iMac, iPod, iPhone, and iPad devices; creating the iTunes Store; launching the "Think different" advertising campaign; and opening the Apple Store retail chain.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs resigned in 2011 for health reasons and died the same year.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] He was succeeded as CEO by Tim Cook, who will be succeeded by John Ternus in September 2026.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Since 2011, Apple has for the most part been the world's largest company by market capitalization, and, as of 2024, is the largest manufacturing company by revenue, the fourth-largest PC vendor, the largest vendor of tablet computers, and the largest vendor of mobile phones.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple became the first publicly traded US company to be valued at over $1 trillion in 2018, and, as of October 2025, is valued at just over $4 trillion.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple has received criticism regarding its contractors' labor conditions, its relationship with trade unions, its environmental practices, and its corporate ethics, including anti-competitive tactics, materials sourcing, and its acquisitions of smaller businesses.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Nevertheless, the company has a large following and enjoys a high level of customer loyalty.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple has consistently been ranked as one of the world's most valuable brands since the late 2000s.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple Computer Company was founded on April 1, 1976, by Steve Jobs, Steve Wozniak, and Ronald Wayne as a partnership.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The company's first product was the Apple I, a computer designed and hand-built entirely by Wozniak.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] To finance its creation, Jobs sold his Volkswagen Bus, and Wozniak sold his HP-65 calculator.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Neither received the full selling price, but together they earned $1,300 (equivalent to $7,400 in 2025).
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak debuted the first prototype Apple I at the Homebrew Computer Club in July 1976.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The Apple I was sold as a motherboard with CPU, RAM, and basic textual-video chips—a base kit concept which was not yet marketed as a complete personal computer.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak later said he was unaware of the coincidental mark of the beast in the number 666, and that he came up with the price because he liked "repeating digits".
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple Computer, Inc. was incorporated in Cupertino, California, on January 3, 1977, without Wayne, who had left and sold his share of the company back to Jobs and Wozniak for $800 only twelve days after having co-founded it.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Multimillionaire Mike Markkula provided essential business expertise and funding of $250,000 (equivalent to $1,328,000 in 2025) to Jobs and Wozniak during the incorporation of Apple.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] During the first five years of operations, revenue grew exponentially, doubling about every four months.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Between September 1977 and September 1980, yearly sales grew from $775,000 to US$118 million, an average annual growth rate of 533%.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The Apple II, also designed by Wozniak, was introduced on April 16, 1977, at the first West Coast Computer Faire.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] It differed from its major rivals, the TRS-80 and Commodore PET, because of its character cell-based color graphics and open architecture.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The Apple I and early Apple II models used ordinary audio cassette tapes as storage devices, which were superseded by the 5+1⁄4-inch floppy disk drive and interface called the Disk II in 1978.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The Apple II was chosen to be the desktop platform for the first killer application of the business world: VisiCalc, a spreadsheet program released in 1979.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] VisiCalc created a business market for the Apple II and gave home users an additional reason to buy an Apple II: compatibility with the office, but Apple II market share remained behind home computers made by competitors such as Atari, Commodore, and Tandy.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] By the end of the day, around 300 millionaires were created, including Jobs and Wozniak, from a stock price of $29 per share and a market cap of $1.778 billion.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In November and December 1979, Steve Jobs and Apple employees, including Jef Raskin, visited Xerox PARC, where they observed the Xerox Alto, featuring a graphical user interface (GUI) and a mouse.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs had negotiated with Xerox in advance to gain access to PARC's technology, in exchange for the right to purchase $1 million worth of Apple's pre-IPO shares.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This visit influenced Jobs to implement a GUI in Apple's products starting with the Apple Lisa in 1983, though he was forced out of the Lisa project during the early development.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Despite being pioneering as a mass-marketed GUI computer, the Lisa suffered from high costs and limited software options, leading to commercial failure.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Following his removal from the Lisa team, Jobs joined the company's Macintosh division in January 1981.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The Macintosh had been envisioned by Jef Raskin as a low-cost, portable computer, and Wozniak had helped its development until a plane crash in early 1981 forced him to step back from the project.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak's absence allowed Jobs to take over the project and he redefined the Macintosh as a mouse-driven GUI machine similar to the Lisa.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak speculates that Jobs' sense of rivalry towards the Lisa project was the driving force behind this sudden shift in direction.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs was also hostile to the Apple II division, which at the time generated most of the company's revenue.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In 1984, Apple launched the Macintosh, the first personal computer without a bundled programming language.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Its debut was signified by "1984", a US$1.5-million television advertisement directed by Ridley Scott that aired during the third quarter of Super Bowl XVIII on January 22, 1984.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This was hailed as a watershed event for Apple's success and was called a "masterpiece" by CNN and one of the greatest TV advertisements of all time by *TV Guide*.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The advertisement created great interest in the Macintosh, and sales were initially good, but began to taper off dramatically after the first three months as reviews started coming in.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs had required 128 kilobytes of RAM, which limited its speed and software in favor of aspiring for a projected price point of $1,000 (equivalent to $3,100 in 2025).
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The Macintosh shipped for $2,495 (equivalent to $7,700 in 2025), a price panned by critics due to its slow performance.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The board of directors instructed Sculley to contain Jobs and his ability to launch expensive forays into untested products.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Rather than submit to Sculley's direction, Jobs attempted to oust him from leadership.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jean-Louis Gassée informed Sculley that Jobs had been attempting to organize a boardroom coup, and called an emergency meeting at which Apple's executive staff sided with Sculley, and stripped Jobs of all operational duties.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs resigned from Apple in September 1985 and took several Apple employees with him to found NeXT.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak had also quit his active employment at Apple earlier in 1985 to pursue other ventures, expressing his frustration with Apple's treatment of the Apple II division and stating that the company had "been going in the wrong direction for the last five years".
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak remained employed by Apple as a representative, receiving a stipend estimated to be $120,000 per year.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs and Wozniak remained Apple shareholders following their departures.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] After the departures of Jobs and Wozniak in 1985, Sculley launched the Macintosh 512K that year with quadruple the RAM, and introduced the LaserWriter, the first reasonably priced PostScript-based laser printer.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] PageMaker, an early desktop publishing application taking advantage of the PostScript language, was also released by Aldus Corporation in July 1985.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] It has been suggested that the combination of Macintosh, LaserWriter, and PageMaker was responsible for the creation of the desktop publishing market.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This dominant position in the desktop publishing market allowed the company to focus on higher price points, the so-called "high-right policy" named for its position on a price–profits chart.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Newer models selling at higher price points offered higher profit margin, and appeared to not affect total sales as power users snapped up every increase in speed.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Although some worried about pricing themselves out of the market, the high-right policy was in full force by the mid-1980s, due to Jean-Louis Gassée's slogan of "fifty-five or die", referring to the 55% profit margins of the Macintosh II.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This policy began to backfire late in the decade as desktop publishing programs appeared on IBM PC compatibles with some of the same functionality of the Macintosh at far lower price points.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The company lost its dominant position in the desktop publishing market and estranged many of its original consumer customer base, who could no longer afford Apple products.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The Christmas season of 1989 was the first in the company's history to have declining sales, which led to a 20% drop in Apple's stock price.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] During this period, the relationship between Sculley and Gassée deteriorated, leading Sculley to effectively demote Gassée in January 1990 by appointing Michael Spindler as the chief operating officer.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Gassée left the company later that year to set up a rival, Be Inc.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The company pivoted its strategy and, in October 1990, introduced three lower-cost models: the Macintosh Classic, the Macintosh LC, and the Macintosh IIsi, all of which generated strong sales.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In 1991, Apple introduced the PowerBook, a commercially successful laptop whose clamshell design influenced later notebook computers.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The same year, Apple introduced System 7, a major upgrade to the Macintosh operating system that introduced a color user interface and improved networking capabilities.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The success of the lower-cost Macintosh models and the PowerBook brought increasing revenue, and the period from 1989 to 1991 was later described by *MacAddict* as the "first golden age" of the Macintosh.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] However, the success of the lower-cost Macintosh models also cannibalized sales of Apple's higher-end systems.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In response, the company introduced several new brands, selling largely identical machines at different price points, for different markets: the high-end Quadra series, the mid-range Centris, and the consumer-oriented Performa.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This led to widespread consumer confusion.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple discontinued the Apple II series in 1993 after encouraging developers and customers to transition to the Macintosh, bringing the company's longest-running product line to an end.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] During the 1990s, Apple also introduced several consumer products, including the QuickTake digital cameras, PowerCD, the Pippin game console, eWorld, Apple Interactive Television Box, and the Newton tablet division.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Although technologically ambitious, they were commercially unsuccessful.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Meanwhile, Microsoft expanded the reach of Windows by focusing on inexpensive personal computers, while Apple continued to emphasize premium hardware with high profit margins.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple unsuccessfully sued Microsoft over similarities between Windows and the Lisa's operating system.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The consumer product flops and the rapid loss of market share to Windows sullied Apple's reputation, and in 1993 Sculley was replaced as CEO by Michael Spindler.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In 1994, Apple, IBM, and Motorola formed the AIM alliance to promote the PowerPC platform.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] That year, Apple introduced the first Power Macintosh models using PowerPC processors.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In the wake of the alliance, Apple opened up to the idea of allowing Motorola and other companies to build Macintosh clones.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Over the next two years, 75 distinct Macintosh clone models were introduced.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] However, by 1996, Apple executives were worried that the clones were cannibalizing sales of its own high-end computers, where profit margins were highest.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In 1996, Spindler was replaced as CEO by Gil Amelio, who was hired for his reputation as a corporate rehabilitator.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Amelio made big changes, including extensive layoffs and cost-cutting.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This period was also marked by repeated attempts to modernize the Macintosh operating system.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The original System 1 was not built for multitasking (running several applications at once), and although Apple introduced cooperative multitasking in System 5, the company concluded that a more modern approach was needed.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Internal efforts, including the Pink project, A/UX, and Copland, failed to produce a suitable successor.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple then sought to acquire an external operating system, first entering negotiations to purchase BeOS.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The talks collapsed when Be CEO and former Apple executive Jean-Louis Gassée demanded $300 million, well above Apple's $125 million offer.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple instead acquired NeXT, the technology company founded by Apple co-founder Steve Jobs after his 1985 ouster from Apple, for its NeXTSTEP operating system.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple would purchase the company for $427 million in cash, stock, stock options, and assumed debt.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] At the insistence of Amelio, Jobs accepted 1.5 million Apple shares as part of the deal rather than an all-cash payment, lending credibility to the acquisition.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Under the agreement, Jobs returned to Apple as an advisor.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The NeXT acquisition was completed on February 7, 1997.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs soon became frustrated with the leadership of Amelio and Apple's board, and in June 1997 anonymously sold his 1.5 million shares, sending the company's stock to a 12-year low.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The stock slide rattled the board, which ousted Amelio as CEO the following month.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs became Apple's *de facto* leader and was formally appointed interim CEO on September 16.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In August 1997, Jobs secured a $150 million investment from Microsoft and a commitment to continue developing software for the Mac platform, an agreement widely viewed as beneficial to both companies following Microsoft's antitrust settlement with the U.S.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs ended the Macintosh clone licensing program, and in September 1997, acquired the largest clone manufacturer, Power Computing.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In November 1997, the online Apple Store launched and adopted a build-to-order manufacturing model similar to that used by Dell.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] By the end of 1997, Jobs had returned Apple to profitability, reporting a profit of $309 million.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs streamlined Apple's product lineup, eliminating roughly 70 percent of existing models and introducing a simplified 'four-quadrant' product strategy consisting of one desktop and one laptop computer each for consumer and professional markets.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The restructuring eliminated approximately 3,000 jobs.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The first major product introduced under this strategy was the iMac, unveiled on May 6, 1998.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Designed by Jony Ive, the all-in-one computer featured a distinctive translucent design enclosure, emphasized Internet connectivity (the "i" in iMac), adopted modern technologies such as USB, and omitted legacy technologies like the floppy disk drive.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] It sold approximately 800,000 units within its first five months on the market.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple completed the transition to the four-quadrant lineup on July 21, 1999, with the introduction of the consumer-oriented iBook laptop.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] It joined the iMac and refined versions of the existing professional Power Macintosh desktop and PowerBook laptop, completing the simplified product matrix.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs said the smaller product lineup allowed Apple to focus more on quality and innovation.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Around then, Apple also completed numerous acquisitions to create a portfolio of digital media production software for both professionals and consumers.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple acquired Macromedia's Key Grip digital video editing software project, which was launched as Final Cut Pro in April 1999.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Key Grip's development also led to Apple's release of the consumer video-editing product iMovie in October 1999.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple acquired the German company Astarte in April 2000, which had developed the DVD authoring software DVDirector, which Apple repackaged as the professional-oriented DVD Studio Pro, and reused its technology to create iDVD for the consumer market.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In 2000, Apple purchased the SoundJam MP audio player software from Casady & Greene.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple renamed the program iTunes, simplified the user interface and added CD burning.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In 2001, Apple changed course with three announcements.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] First, on March 24, 2001, Apple announced the release of a new modern operating system, Mac OS X.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This was after numerous failed attempts in the early 1990s, and several years of development.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Mac OS X is based on NeXTSTEP, OpenStep, and BSD Unix, to combine the stability, reliability, and security of Unix with the ease of use of an overhauled user interface.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Second, in May 2001, the first two Apple Store retail locations opened in Virginia and California, offering an improved presentation of the company's products.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] At the time, many speculated that the stores would fail, but they later expanded to more than 500 locations worldwide.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Third, on October 23, 2001, the iPod portable digital audio player debuted.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The product was first sold on November 10, 2001, and sold over 100 million units within six years.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In 2003, the iTunes Store was introduced with music downloads for 99¢ a song and iPod integration.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] It quickly became the market leader in online music services, with over 5 billion downloads by June 19, 2008.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Two years later, the iTunes Store was the world's largest music retailer.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In 2002, Apple purchased Nothing Real for its advanced digital compositing application Shake, and Emagic for the music productivity application Logic.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The purchase of Emagic made Apple the first computer manufacturer to own a music software company.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The acquisition was followed by the development of Apple's consumer-level GarageBand application.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The release of iPhoto that year completed the iLife suite.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] At the Worldwide Developers Conference keynote address on June 6, 2005, Jobs announced that Apple would move away from PowerPC processors, and the Mac would transition to Intel processors in 2006.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] On January 10, 2006, the new MacBook Pro and iMac became the first Apple computers to use Intel's Core Duo CPU.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] By August 7, 2006, Apple made the transition to Intel chips for the entire Mac product line—over one year sooner than announced.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The Power Mac, iBook, and PowerBook brands were retired during the transition; the Mac Pro, MacBook, and MacBook Pro became their respective successors.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple also introduced Boot Camp in 2006 to help users install Windows XP or Windows Vista on their Intel Macs alongside Mac OS X.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Between early 2003 and 2006, the price of Apple's stock increased more than tenfold, from around $6 per share (split-adjusted) to over $80.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] When Apple surpassed Dell's market cap in January 2006, Jobs sent an email to Apple employees saying Dell's CEO Michael Dell should eat his words.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Nine years prior, Dell had said that if he ran Apple he would "shut it down and give the money back to the shareholders".
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] During his keynote speech at the Macworld Expo on January 9, 2007, Jobs announced the renaming of Apple Computer, Inc. to Apple Inc., because the company had broadened its focus from computers to consumer electronics.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This event also saw the announcement of the iPhone and the Apple TV.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The company sold 270,000 first-generation iPhones during the first 30 hours of sales, and some industry commentators described the device as "a game changer for the industry".
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In an article posted on Apple's website on February 6, 2007, Jobs wrote that Apple would be willing to sell music on the iTunes Store without digital rights management, thereby allowing tracks to be played on third-party players if record labels would agree to drop the technology.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] On April 2, 2007, Apple and EMI jointly announced the removal of DRM technology from EMI's catalog in the iTunes Store, effective in May 2007.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Other record labels eventually followed suit and Apple published a press release in January 2009 to announce that all songs on the iTunes Store are available without its FairPlay DRM.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In July 2008, Apple launched the App Store to sell third-party applications for the iPhone and iPod Touch.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Within a month, the store sold 60 million applications and registered an average daily revenue of $1 million, with Jobs speculating in August 2008 that the App Store could become a billion-dollar business for Apple.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] By October 2008, Apple was the third-largest mobile handset supplier in the world due to the popularity of the iPhone.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] On January 14, 2009, Jobs announced in an internal memo that he would be taking a six-month medical leave of absence from Apple until the end of June 2009 and would spend the time focusing on his health.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In the email, Jobs stated that "the curiosity over my personal health continues to be a distraction not only for me and my family, but everyone else at Apple as well", and explained that the break would allow the company "to focus on delivering extraordinary products".
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Though Jobs was absent, Apple recorded its best non-holiday quarter (Q1 FY 2009) during the recession, with revenue of $8.16 billion and profit of $1.21 billion.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] After years of speculation and multiple rumored "leaks", Apple unveiled a large screen, tablet-like media device known as the iPad on January 27, 2010.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The iPad ran the same touch-based operating system as the iPhone, and all iPhone apps were compatible with the iPad.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This gave the iPad a large app catalog on launch, though having very little development time before the release.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Later that year on April 3, 2010, the iPad was launched in the US.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] It sold more than 300,000 units on its first day, and 500,000 by the end of the first week.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In May 2010, Apple's market cap exceeded that of competitor Microsoft for the first time since 1989.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In June 2010, Apple released the iPhone 4, which introduced video calling using FaceTime, multitasking, and a new design with an exposed stainless steel frame as the phone's antenna system.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Later that year, Apple again refreshed the iPod line by introducing a multi-touch iPod Nano, an iPod Touch with FaceTime, and an iPod Shuffle that brought back the clickwheel buttons of earlier generations.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] It also introduced the smaller, cheaper second-generation Apple TV which allowed the rental of movies and shows.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] On January 17, 2011, Jobs announced in an internal Apple memo that he would take another medical leave of absence for an indefinite period to allow him to focus on his health.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Chief operating officer Tim Cook assumed Jobs' day-to-day operations at Apple, although Jobs would still remain "involved in major strategic decisions".
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple became the most valuable consumer-facing brand in the world, and has consistently been among the most valuable brands since then.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] In June 2011, Jobs took the stage and unveiled iCloud, an online storage and syncing service for music, photos, files, and software which replaced MobileMe, Apple's previous attempt at content syncing.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This would be the last product launch Jobs would attend before his death.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] On August 24, 2011, Jobs resigned his position as CEO of Apple due to his health issues.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] He was replaced by Cook and Jobs became Apple's chairman.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple did not have a chairman at the time and instead had two co-lead directors, Andrea Jung and Arthur D.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Levinson, who continued with those titles until Levinson replaced Jobs as chairman of the board in November after Jobs' death.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] On October 5, 2011, Steve Jobs died, marking the end of an era for Apple.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] The next major product announcement by Apple was on January 19, 2012, when Apple's Phil Schiller introduced iBooks Textbooks for iOS and iBooks Author for Mac OS X in New York City.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Jobs stated in the biography *Steve Jobs* that he wanted to reinvent the textbook industry and education.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] These launches were successful, with the iPhone 5 (released September 21, 2012) becoming Apple's biggest iPhone launch with over two million pre-orders and sales of three million iPads in three days following the launch of the iPad Mini and fourth-generation iPad (released November 3, 2012).
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Apple also released a third-generation 13-inch MacBook Pro with a Retina display and new iMac and Mac Mini computers.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] On August 20, 2012, Apple's rising stock price increased the company's market capitalization to a then-record $624 billion.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] This beat the non-inflation-adjusted record for market capitalization previously set by Microsoft in 1999.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] On August 24, 2012, a US jury ruled that Samsung should pay Apple $1.05 billion (£665m) in damages in an intellectual property lawsuit.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] Samsung appealed the damages award, which was reduced by $450 million and further granted Samsung's request for a new trial.
[src:magsafe/apple-inc-p01] On November 10, 2012, Apple confirmed a global settlement that dismissed all existing lawsuits between Apple and HTC up to that date, in favor of a ten-year license agreement for current and future patents between the two companies.
